  urldate = {2024-12-01},
  abstract = {JWST has revealed a ubiquitous population of ``little red dots'' (LRDs) at \$z\textbackslash gtrsim4\$, selected via their red rest-frame optical emission and compact morphologies. They are thought to be reddened by dust, whether in tori of active galactic nuclei or the interstellar medium (ISM), though none have direct dust detections to date. Informed by the average characteristics of 675 LRDs drawn from the literature, we provide ballpark constraints on the dust characteristics of the LRD population and estimate they have average dust masses of \$\textbackslash langle M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm dust\textbraceright\textbackslash rangle=(1.6\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +4.8\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.9\textbraceright )\textbackslash times10\textasciicircum\textbraceleft 4\textbraceright{} M\_\textbackslash odot\$, luminosities of \$\textbackslash langle L\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm IR\textbraceright\textbackslash rangle=(8\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +3\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -5\textbraceright )\textbackslash times10\textasciicircum\textbraceleft 10\textbraceright{} L\_\textbackslash odot\$ and temperatures of \$\textbackslash langle T\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm dust\textbraceright\textbackslash rangle=110\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +21\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -36\textbraceright\$ K. Notably, the spectral energy distributions are thought to peak at \$\textbackslash sim\$100 K (rest-frame 20-30 \$\textbackslash mu\$m) regardless of heating mechanism, whether AGN or star formation. LRDs' compact sizes \$R\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm eff\textbraceright\textbackslash sim100\$ pc are the dominant factor contributing to their low estimated dust masses. Our predictions likely mean LRDs have, on average, submillimeter emission a factor of \$\textbackslash sim\$100\$\textbackslash times\$ fainter than current ALMA limits provide. The star-to-dust ratio is a factor \$\textbackslash sim\$100\$\textbackslash times\$ larger than expected from dust formation models if one assumes the rest-optical light is dominated by stars; this suggests stars do not dominate. Despite their high apparent volume density, LRDs contribute negligibly (0.1\%) to the cosmic dust budget at \$z\textbackslash gtrsim4\$ due to their low dust masses.},
