  urldate = {2024-03-04},
  abstract = {We present the first cosmology results from large-scale structure in the Dark Energy Survey (DES) spanning 5000 deg\$\textasciicircum 2\$. We perform an analysis combining three two-point correlation functions (3\$\textbackslash times\$2pt): (i) cosmic shear using 100 million source galaxies, (ii) galaxy clustering, and (iii) the cross-correlation of source galaxy shear with lens galaxy positions. The analysis was designed to mitigate confirmation or observer bias; we describe specific changes made to the lens galaxy sample following unblinding of the results. We model the data within the flat \$\textbackslash Lambda\$CDM and \$w\$CDM cosmological models. We find consistent cosmological results between the three two-point correlation functions; their combination yields clustering amplitude \$S\_8=0.776\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.017\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.017\textbraceright\$ and matter density \$\textbackslash Omega\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft m\textbraceright\textbraceright{} = 0.339\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.032\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.031\textbraceright\$ in \$\textbackslash Lambda\$CDM, mean with 68\% confidence limits; \$S\_8=0.775\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.026\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.024\textbraceright\$, \$\textbackslash Omega\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft m\textbraceright\textbraceright{} = 0.352\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.035\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.041\textbraceright\$, and dark energy equation-of-state parameter \$w=-0.98\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.32\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.20\textbraceright\$ in \$w\$CDM. This combination of DES data is consistent with the prediction of the model favored by the Planck 2018 cosmic microwave background (CMB) primary anisotropy data, which is quantified with a probability-to-exceed \$p=0.13\$ to \$0.48\$. When combining DES 3\$\textbackslash times\$2pt data with available baryon acoustic oscillation, redshift-space distortion, and type Ia supernovae data, we find \$p=0.34\$. Combining all of these data sets with Planck CMB lensing yields joint parameter constraints of \$S\_8 = 0.812\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.008\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.008\textbraceright\$, \$\textbackslash Omega\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft m\textbraceright\textbraceright{} = 0.306\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.004\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.005\textbraceright\$, \$h=0.680\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.004\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.003\textbraceright\$, and \$\textbackslash sum m\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash nu\textbraceright{$<$}0.13 \textbackslash;\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft eV\textbackslash; (95\textbackslash\% \textbackslash;CL)\textbraceright\$ in \$\textbackslash Lambda\$CDM; \$S\_8 = 0.812\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.008\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.008\textbraceright\$, \$\textbackslash Omega\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft m\textbraceright\textbraceright{} = 0.302\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.006\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.006\textbraceright\$, \$h=0.687\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.006\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.007\textbraceright\$, and \$w=-1.031\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.030\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.027\textbraceright\$ in \$w\$CDM. (abridged)},
