  urldate = {2025-12-03},
  abstract = {We present the first catalogue of strong lensing galaxy clusters identified in the Euclid Quick Release 1 observations (covering \$63.1\textbackslash,\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft deg\textasciicircum 2\textbraceright\$). This catalogue is the result of the visual inspection of 1260 cluster fields. Each galaxy cluster was ranked with a probability, \$\textbackslash mathcal\textbraceleft P\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft lens\textbraceright\textbraceright\$, based on the number and plausibility of the identified strong lensing features. Specifically, we identified 83 gravitational lenses with \$\textbackslash mathcal\textbraceleft P\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft lens\textbraceright\textbraceright{$>$}0.5\$, of which 14 have \$\textbackslash mathcal\textbraceleft P\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft lens\textbraceright\textbraceright =1\$, and clearly exhibiting secure strong lensing features, such as giant tangential and radial arcs, and multiple images. Considering the measured number density of lensing galaxy clusters, approximately \$0.3\textbackslash,\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft deg\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft -2\textbraceright\$ for \$\textbackslash mathcal\textbraceleft P\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft lens\textbraceright\textbraceright{$>$}0.9\$, we predict that \textbackslash Euclid\textbackslash{} will likely see more than 4500 strong lensing clusters over the course of the mission. Notably, only three of the identified cluster-scale lenses had been previously observed from space. Thus, \textbackslash Euclid has provided the first high-resolution imaging for the remaining \$80\$ galaxy cluster lenses, including those with the highest probability. The identified strong lensing features will be used for training deep-learning models for identifying gravitational arcs and multiple images automatically in \textbackslash Euclid observations. This study confirms the huge potential of \textbackslash Euclid for finding new strong lensing clusters, enabling exciting new discoveries on the nature of dark matter and dark energy and the study of the high-redshift Universe.},
