  abstract = {We present the properties of two candidate massive (\$M\_\textbackslash star\textbackslash sim10\textasciicircum\textbraceleft 11\textbraceright M\_\textbackslash odot\$) and dusty (\$A\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm v\textbraceright{$>$}2.5\$ mag) galaxies at \$z=5-7\$ in the first 0.28 deg\$\textasciicircum 2\$ of the COSMOS-Web survey. One object is spectroscopically confirmed at \$z\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm spec\textbraceright =5.051\$, while the other has a robust \$z\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm phot\textbraceright =6.7\textbackslash pm0.3\$. Thanks to their extremely red colors (\$F277W-F444W\textbackslash sim1.7\$ mag), these galaxies satisfy the nominal color-selection for the widely-studied ``little red dot" (LRD) population with the exception of their spatially-resolved morphologies. The morphology of our targets allows us to conclude that their red continuum is dominated by highly obscured stellar emission and not by reddened nuclear activity. Using a variety of SED-fitting tools and star formation histories, we estimate the stellar masses to be \$\textbackslash log(M\_\textbackslash star)=11.32\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.07\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.15\textbraceright\$ \$M\_\textbackslash odot\$ and \$\textbackslash log(M\_\textbackslash star)=11.2\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.1\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.2\textbraceright\$ \$M\_\textbackslash odot\$, respectively, with a red continuum emission dominated by a recent episode of star formation. We then compare their number density to the halo mass function to infer stellar baryon fractions of \$\textbackslash epsilon\_\textbackslash star\textbackslash sim0.25\$ and \$\textbackslash epsilon\_\textbackslash star\textbackslash sim0.5\$. Both are significantly higher than what is commonly observed in lower-z galaxies or more dust-obscured galaxies at similar redshifts. With very bright ultra-high-z Lyman-Break Galaxies and some non-AGN dominated LRDs, such ``extended" LRDs represent another population that may require very efficient star formation at early times.},
