  urldate = {2025-10-02},
  abstract = {We measure cosmic weak lensing shear power spectra with the Subaru Hyper Suprime-Cam (HSC) survey first-year shear catalog covering 137deg\$\textasciicircum 2\$ of the sky. Thanks to the high effective galaxy number density of \$\textbackslash sim\$17 arcmin\$\textasciicircum\textbraceleft -2\textbraceright\$ even after conservative cuts such as magnitude cut of \$i{$<$}24.5\$ and photometric redshift cut of \$0.3\textbackslash leq z \textbackslash leq 1.5\$, we obtain a high significance measurement of the cosmic shear power spectra in 4 tomographic redshift bins, achieving a total signal-to-noise ratio of 16 in the multipole range \$300 \textbackslash leq \textbackslash ell \textbackslash leq 1900\$. We carefully account for various uncertainties in our analysis including the intrinsic alignment of galaxies, scatters and biases in photometric redshifts, residual uncertainties in the shear measurement, and modeling of the matter power spectrum. The accuracy of our power spectrum measurement method as well as our analytic model of the covariance matrix are tested against realistic mock shear catalogs. For a flat \$\textbackslash Lambda\$ cold dark matter (\$\textbackslash Lambda\$CDM) model, we find \$S\_8\textbackslash equiv \textbackslash sigma\_8(\textbackslash Omega\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm m\textbraceright/0.3)\textasciicircum\textbackslash alpha=0.800\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.029\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.028\textbraceright\$ for \$\textbackslash alpha=0.45\$ (\$S\_8=0.780\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.030\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.033\textbraceright\$ for \$\textbackslash alpha=0.5\$) from our HSC tomographic cosmic shear analysis alone. In comparison with Planck cosmic microwave background constraints, our results prefer slightly lower values of \$S\_8\$, although metrics such as the Bayesian evidence ratio test do not show significant evidence for discordance between these results. We study the effect of possible additional systematic errors that are unaccounted in our fiducial cosmic shear analysis, and find that they can shift the best-fit values of \$S\_8\$ by up to \$\textbackslash sim 0.6\textbackslash sigma\$ in both directions. The full HSC survey data will contain several times more area, and will lead to significantly improved cosmological constraints.},
