  urldate = {2025-02-11},
  abstract = {We introduce redMaGiC, an automated algorithm for selecting Luminous Red Galaxies (LRGs). The algorithm was specifically developed to minimize photometric redshift uncertainties in photometric large-scale structure studies. redMaGiC achieves this by self-training the color-cuts necessary to produce a luminosity-thresholded LRG sample of constant comoving density. We demonstrate that redMaGiC photozs are very nearly as accurate as the best machine-learning based methods, yet they require minimal spectroscopic training, do not suffer from extrapolation biases, and are very nearly Gaussian. We apply our algorithm to Dark Energy Survey (DES) Science Verification (SV) data to produce a redMaGiC catalog sampling the redshift range \$z\textbackslash in[0.2,0.8]\$. Our fiducial sample has a comoving space density of \$10\textasciicircum\textbraceleft -3\textbraceright\textbackslash{} (h\textasciicircum\textbraceleft -1\textbraceright{} Mpc)\textasciicircum\textbraceleft -3\textbraceright\$, and a median photoz bias (\$z\_\textbraceleft spec\textbraceright -z\_\textbraceleft photo\textbraceright\$) and scatter \$(\textbackslash sigma\_z/(1+z))\$ of 0.005 and 0.017 respectively. The corresponding \$5\textbackslash sigma\$ outlier fraction is 1.4\%. We also test our algorithm with Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS) Data Release 8 (DR8) and Stripe 82 data, and discuss how spectroscopic training can be used to control photoz biases at the 0.1\% level.},
