  urldate = {2024-12-20},
  abstract = {We report the discovery of an ultra-massive grand-design red spiral galaxy, named Zh\textbackslash 'ul\textbackslash 'ong (Torch Dragon), at \$z\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm phot\textbraceright{} = 5.2\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.3\textbraceright\_\textbraceleft -0.2\textbraceright\$ in the JWST PANORAMIC survey, identified as the most distant bulge+disk galaxy with spiral arms known to date. Zh\textbackslash 'ul\textbackslash 'ong displays an extraordinary combination of properties: 1) a classical bulge centered in a large, face-on exponential stellar disk (half-light radius of \$R\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash rm e\textbraceright{} = 3.7 \textbackslash pm 0.1 \textbackslash, \textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft kpc\textbraceright\$), with spiral arms extending across 19 kpc; 2) a clear transition from the red, quiescent core (\$F150W-F444W=3.1\$ mag) with high stellar mass surface density (\$\textbackslash log(\textbackslash Sigma M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash star\textbraceright/M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash odot\textbraceright{} \textbackslash, \textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft kpc\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft -2\textbraceright ) = 9.91\_\textbraceleft -0.09\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.11\textbraceright\$) to the star-forming outer regions, as revealed by spatially resolved SED analysis, which indicates significant inside-out galaxy growth; 3) an extremely high stellar mass at its redshift, with \$\textbackslash log (M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash star\textbraceright/M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash odot\textbraceright )=11.03\_\textbraceleft -0.08\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +0.10\textbraceright\$ comparable to the Milky Way, and an implied baryon-to-star conversion efficiency (\$\textbackslash epsilon \textbackslash sim 0.3\$) that is 1.5 times higher than even the most efficient galaxies at later epochs; 4) despite an active disk, a relatively modest overall star formation rate (\$\textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft SFR\textbraceright{} =66\_\textbraceleft -46\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft +89\textbraceright{} \textasciitilde M\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash odot\textbraceright{} \textbackslash, \textbackslash mathrm\textbraceleft yr\textbraceright\textasciicircum\textbraceleft -1\textbraceright\$), which is \${$>\$$}0.5 dex below the star formation main sequence at \$z \textbackslash sim 5.2\$ and \${$>\$$}10 times lower than ultra-massive dusty galaxies at \$z=5-6\$. Altogether, Zh\textbackslash 'ul\textbackslash 'ong shows that mature galaxies emerged much earlier than expected in the first billion years after the Big Bang through rapid galaxy formation and morphological evolution. Our finding offers key constraints for models of massive galaxy formation and the origin of spiral structures in the early universe.},
